  "prompt": "What is the procedure for 48 days Lord Murugan fasting?",
  "response": "The 48-day fasting dedicated to Lord Murugan, also known as the Skanda Sashti Vratham, is a significant spiritual practice in Hinduism, particularly among Tamil devotees. Here\u2019s a general outline of how this fasting is observed:\n\n1. **Duration**: The fasting is observed for 48 days, typically starting on the Pradhamai (the day after Amavasya, the new moon) and concluding on the Sashti Tithi after the new moon day of the Tamil month of Aippasi (October-November).\n\n2. **Fasting and Diet**:\n   - Many devotees opt for a vegetarian diet throughout the 48 days. Some may also choose a more austere path, consuming only a single meal a day or refraining from solid foods entirely on certain days.\n   - Avoidance of onion, garlic, and other 'rajasic' and 'tamasic' foods is common.\n   - Consumption of alcohol, tobacco, and other intoxicants is strictly avoided.\n\n3. **Daily Rituals**:\n   - **Abhishekam**: Devotees perform or sponsor abhishekam (sacred bath) for a Murugan idol or visit a temple where this ceremony is conducted.\n   - **Prayers and Bhajans**: Daily prayers, recitation of Skanda-related mantras, such as the \"Skanda Shasti Kavacham,\" and participation in bhajans (devotional songs) are common practices.\n   - **Meditation and Yoga**: Engaging in meditation and yoga can be a part of the spiritual routine to enhance self-discipline and focus.\n\n4. **Visiting Temples**: \n   - Devotees visit Murugan temples regularly, especially on Tuesdays and Fridays, which are considered auspicious.\n   - Participating in special poojas, rituals, and ceremonies conducted in temples can be a part of the observance.\n   \n5. **Final Days**:\n   - The last six days are particularly significant, starting from the day of the lunar month known as Sashti, culminating in Soorasamharam day (the day Lord Murugan defeated the demon Soorapadman).\n   - Devotees might observe stricter fasting in these final days, involving additional prayers and temple visits.\n\n6. **Soorasamharam**:\n   - On the final day, dramatic reenactments and processions may be held in temples to celebrate the victory of Lord Murugan over the asura Soorapadman.\n   - Devotees often participate in these events, which are filled with vibrant colors, music, and fervor.\n\nThese practices might vary among communities and individuals. Devotees may choose to adapt practices to their personal capacity and spiritual goals while maintaining the underlying principles of devotion, purity, and discipline. Consulting with elders or spiritual leaders in the community can further guide personalized fasting rituals.",
